	pages = {354 - 369},
	doi = {10.47750/QAS/27.212.33},
	url = {https://www.scopus.com/pages/publications/105037139446?origin=resultslist},
	affiliations = {Accounting Department, Faculty of Economics and Business, Padang State University, Indonesia; Accounting Study Program, School of Economics and Business, Telkom University, Indonesia; Business Administration Department, Faculty of Social and Political Science, Halu Oleo University, Indonesia; Accounting Department, BINUS Online Learning, Bina Nusantara University, Indonesia},
	abstract = {The rapid expansion of fintech peer-to-peer lending in Indonesia has transformed financial intermediation by improving access to credit while exposing firms to new managerial and technological challenges. This study investigates how predictive and governance capabilities jointly enhance operational efficiency within this sector. It specifically examines how machine learning-based credit scoring and cyber risk management function as integrated managerial control systems that support financial sustainability and ethical governance. A quantitative design was employed, combining Data Envelopment Analysis (DEA) to measure firm-level efficiency and Partial Least Squares Structural Equation Modeling (PLS-SEM) to test relationships among predictive, governance, and performance variables. Data from ninety-one licensed fintech firms provided comprehensive evidence of operational outcomes and control mechanisms. Results reveal that both machine learning credit scoring and cyber risk management have significant positive effects on efficiency. Their interaction explains 48.2 percent of the variance in performance, indicating that predictive accuracy and governance resilience operate as complementary control mechanisms that improve decision quality, cost discipline, and organizational reliability. The findings imply that digital innovation must be embedded within strong governance frameworks to ensure responsible financial management. Managers and policymakers should integrate predictive analytics and cyber governance indicators into performance dashboards and control systems. This study contributes novel insights by conceptualizing predictive and protective managerial capabilities as a hybrid control framework. It advances managerial accounting theory by linking technology, governance, and control to sustainable operational efficiency and by offering a strategic model for responsible fintech management. © 2026, SRAC - Romanian Society for Quality. All rights reserved.},
