	abstract = {This study employs panel data from 31 provincial-level regions in China (excluding Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Macao) spanning 2009–2023 and applies baseline regression, moderating effect, and threshold regression models to systematically examine the intrinsic relationship between digital finance, artificial intelligence (AI) development, and government governance capacity. Notably, 1) AI development significantly enhances government governance capacity, with the magnitude of this effect varying across regions with different levels of human capital. 2) Digital finance plays a critical moderating role between AI development and government governance capacity, with its moderating effect exhibiting certain heterogeneity across regions characterized by varying degrees of financial and external openness. 3) The positive impact of AI on government governance capacity is progressively strengthened as regional economic development increases, demonstrating a significant threshold-based incremental effect. These findings provide a robust theoretical basis and policy-oriented insights for promoting the deep integration of AI and digital finance along with advancing the modernization of government governance capacity. Copyright © 2026. Published by Elsevier Inc.},
