	abstract = {The development of Artificial Intelligence (AI) technology has had a significant impact on digital transformation across sectors. However, the adoption rate of this technology remains variable and faces several challenges, ranging from perceived usefulness to trust in the system. This study aims to identify factors influencing the adoption of AI technology through a Systematic Literature Review (SLR) approach using the Technology Acceptance Model (TAM) framework. The analysis was conducted on 55 scientific articles published between 2020 and August, 2025 and obtained from reputable databases. The synthesis results indicate that the primary constructs of TAM, namely Perceived Usefulness (PU) and Perceived Ease of Use (PEOU), are dominant predictors of Behavioral Intention (BI). Furthermore, external factors such as Trust, Subjective Norms, Perceived Risk, and Facilitating Conditions have also been shown to strengthen the model in explaining the dynamics of AI adoption. These findings demonstrate that the application of TAM is contextual, depending on the sector and geographic location. This study is expected to provide conceptual and practical contributions in designing AI technology implementation strategies that are more effective, inclusive, and adaptive to user needs. © 2025 IEEE.},
