	abstract = {The compliance of sustainability in mobile communication systems has become a burning topic, as the active use of mobile networks, in particular 5G networks, has increased energy consumption and levels of carbon emissions significantly. The current research paper discusses how the international standards and legal frameworks can contribute towards the development of green ICT practices and thereby reduce environmental footprint of the mobile systems without interfering with the efficiency of the mobile system. The exploration highlighted the importance of ISO/IEC standards, ITU-T recommendations, and 3GPP specifications as the main compliance tools that allow mobile operators to quantify, track, and systematically reduce the environmental effects of their operations. Moreover, this study examines the regulatory frameworks in jurisdictions enforcing binding sustainability obligations on ICT providers, such as carbon-cutting policies, energy-saving policies, and circular economy policies. This study addresses the implementation solutions for the integration of these standards and legal requirements in mobile systems, which involves governance structures, energy management, compliance with the circle of economy, and data-driven monitoring of compliance. This paper further discusses issues and future research opportunities in the area of sustainability compliance, such as harmonizing the standards, evaluating the sustainability of emerging technology, compliance enforcement, and equity-based approach to the compliance framework. The paper ends by giving policy recommendations and further directions to take green ICT, especially the development of unified global governance systems, the strengthening of the regulations of the circular-economy, and funding research that can aid in improving sustainability issues related to new technologies. © 2026 IEEE.},
